node.text:
Hey guys, Artem from the Calisthenics School is here ✋🏻

💪🏻 You were very interested in the post about multifunctional trainings, and I promised to continue this topic and tell you about multifunctional exercises. If you have not read the previous one, then be sure to come back to it a little later to understand what a multifunctional workout is.
⠀
🤔 At first I thought it would be logical to show several exercises that can be combined into a workout. But when it comes to multifunctional exercises, there are so many details that I need to explain to you! Therefore, I decided to do a series of analyzes one exercise at a time, and we will start with push-ups.
⠀
One of the coolest multi-functional push-ups for beginners and intermediate athletes is the archer push-up

Scroll through the carousel to see the technique, target muscles and simplification
🔥🔥TODAY IS THE LAST DAY OF COUPON CODE ‘BASICS’!🔥🔥

You will find more cool and interesting solutions in the Basic Course - 97 video exercises, 4 levels of difficulty, 21 training programs for different aims

Link in bio of @calisthenicsschool ⬆️

node.text:
MULTIFUNCIONAL TRAININGS⬇️

📝Multifunctional training is a set of complex exercises that develop a person's strength, endurance, flexibility and coordination.
⠀
This type of training has been known since ancient times: this is how gladiators trained to be prepared for a battle. The same training principles are used by modern gymnasts.
⠀
💪🏻Multifunctional training is possible without additional equipment - you can train individually, at home or outdoors.
⠀
In short, these are training sessions that comprehensively develop the human body. I can already see how you think: ‘Come on! What should I do?’ Okay, okay, cards on the table.
⠀
👊🏻Behind the scenes, there are narrowly focused and more multifunctional exercises. Your task is to create a circuit workout with long pauses between circles and small pauses between exercises.

PASSIVE AND ACTIVE HANGING ⬇️ 
⠀
All pulling exercises start from a hang. But which hanging technique is the best?
⠀
Wait there are different hanging techniques? Of course, there are!
⠀
And it's not about the grip how some of you might have thought. It's THE HANG, which has two basic variations: active and passive.
⠀
Let's see the difference:
⠀
1️⃣ PASSIVE
⠀
It's just a usual hang you are familiar with. Just grab the bar, fully relax your body and hang.
⠀
💪 Muscles involved
Only forearms work in this position.
⠀
2️⃣ ACTIVE
⠀
Now it gets more interesting. "Activating" the passive hang allows you to INVOLVE THE NEEDED MUSCLES at the beginning of any pulling exercise and helps you CONTROL THE TECHNIQUE and TARGET THE MUSCLES even better.
⠀
💪 Muscles involved
Additionally to the forearms, you activate trapezius, rhomboid, teres major and minor muscles, and of course lats.
⠀
❓But you might have a lot of questions:
⠀
How to do it correctly?
Are there differences in the active hang in different exercises?
Which pulling exercises MUST NOT be performed with the active hang?
⠀
All this you will learn from a NEW VIDEO on our YOUTUBE CHANNEL tomorrow! Find the link in the stories highlights and definitely SUBSCRIBE and turn on the notifications 😉
⠀
See you there!
⠀

CALISTHENICS FOR NEWBIES. WHERE TO BEGIN? ⬇️
⠀
Many beginners start their calisthenics journey INCORRECTLY aiming at spectacular elements right away. Therefore, they burn out quickly, get injured and see no progress.
⠀
To avoid this shall you begin WITH BASICS. It will help you start smoothly,  gradually increasing loads to prepare your body for calisthenics elements like planche, front lever, handstand, etc.
⠀
5 STEPS THAT WILL HELP YOU ACHIEVE YOUR FIRST RESULTS:
⠀
1️⃣ Determine your level
⠀
Perform each of these exercises on max:
⠀
🔸 Dips
🔸 Push-ups
🔸 Pull-ups
🔸 Hanging legs raises
⠀
IMPORTANT! Do not squeeze out the last reps in convulsions! When you feel the quality of your performance drops, you should stop.
⠀
* If you can't pull up, do it on a low horizontal bar, helping yourself with bent legs standing on the ground.
⠀
2️⃣ Set your first goal
⠀
The ideal goal for the first month is to increase your maximum for each exercise by 3-4 reps.
⠀
3️⃣ Choose exercises
⠀
To prevent your body from getting used to the same type of load, use different types of similar exercises.
⠀
Example: wide pull-ups + chin-ups + Australian pull-ups.
⠀
The main point is to choose exercises that you can do with proper technique.
⠀
4️⃣ Make a training program
⠀
✔️ 5-7 exercises in one training session.
✔️ Do 80-90% of your max quantity (if you do 10 pull-ups, then do 8-9 reps)
✔️ Rest between exercises and sets — 2 minutes.
⠀
If you want ready-to-go training programs, lots of unique exercises aimed at different muscle groups and calisthenics elements, follow the link in bio and check out our courses.
⠀
They are bundled now with a 34% discount so hurry up and become a CALISTHENICS MASTER 😎
⠀
5️⃣ JUST DO IT!
⠀
All the above points are useless without practice. Continue training at least 3 times per week, and soon you will see the results 😉
⠀
Save this post and use it as a cheat sheet 😉
⠀
Train smart with The Calisthenics School 🔥
⠀

SECRET PLANCHE MUSCLE ⬇️
⠀
Hey, calisthenics community! Artem is here 👋
⠀
Few people talk about the importance of back muscles for planche. You only hear on every corner "STRONG SHOULDERS, YOU'LL NEED STRONG SHOULDERS!"
⠀
But the back muscles are nonetheless important and If you don't involve them in the work correctly, then all the load will fall on the shoulders and biceps. This makes it harder for you to learn the element and leads to injuries.
⠀
💪 ANATOMY
⠀
If we consider the back muscles, a huge role is played by the muscled called latissimus dorsi.
⠀
Squeezing that muscle, you create a kinda muscle corset, therefore, an additional vector of forces directed upward, that is so necessary to do planche.
⠀
Now let's learn how to properly work the lats. To do this, we will use STRAIGHT-ARM PLANK SHRUGS 🔥
⠀
⚙️ TECHNIQUE
⠀
❌ INCORRECT
Get into the straight-arm plank position and then FORCE your body down dropping in shoulders. Your arms remain straight. Now push the floor away from you as hard as you can protracting your back as hard as possible (see the video).
⠀
In this case, the main load will fall on the chest muscles and this exercise will become super useless for planche!
⠀
✅ CORRECT
Get into the straight-arm plank position. Relax all the back and shoulder muscles so your body drops down under its own weight. The arms remain straight.
⠀
Now, working ONLY with your lats and excluding chest muscles, push yourself up into the hollow body position. In this position, you should feel how your lats are tensed (see the other video).
⠀
With this technique, the exercise will work as intended and you will learn how to work with lats to boost your planche 😎
⠀
When teaching the calisthenics elements, I always pay attention to ALL the necessary muscles and select only the most effective exercises for everyone!

Practicing with my "1000% Ultimate Planche" course you will work only on the needed muscles and build the CORRECT technique. This will help you learn the planche as fast as possible without mistakes and injuries 🔥
⠀

⠀

☠️ THE WORST FRONT LEVER EXERCISES ☠️

Hey, calisthenics community 👋 Artem the rescuer here!
⠀
Why the rescuer? Because today I will rescue you from BAD FRONT LEVER EXERCISES 😈
⠀
There are many exercises that are useless or aimed at completely different muscles than you need for the element. And there are even those that can hurt your progress!
⠀
❌ FRONT LEVER WITH A RUBBER BAND
⠀
One of the goals of preparational exercises is to work on the neuromuscular connection (the connection between brain and muscles 🧠 ↔️ 💪). The better the connection, the more the brain engages the muscles in the work when you perform any element.
⠀
In order for this connection to become fully established, you need to put the muscles under the same amount of load as when performing the element itself.
⠀
The rubber band will ease the element and reduce the load on your muscles. Therefore, the needed neuromuscular connection won't be formed.
⠀
If you perform the front lever with a rubber band, you will learn to do the front lever with a rubber band. But as soon as you remove the band the progress is gone.
⠀
❌ ONE-LEGGED FRONT LEVER
⠀
The front lever is performed mainly by the back muscles, glutes, and abs. When you do the one-legged front lever, the abs DON'T get involved in the work!
⠀
Try it yourself: lie on your back, bend one leg and press it to your chest. Extend the other leg, but do not touch the floor with it (let it hang in the air). Pay attention to the abs and how much it's involved.
⠀
Now stretch out the bent leg, but still do not touch the floor. Do you feel the difference?
⠀
The one-legged front lever does not load your abdominals. Therefore, they won't become strong enough and you will be moving nowhere!
⠀
Let me know in the comments below if you want the same post about planche ⬇️
⠀
And if you want to use only the most effective exercises in your front lever practice, then I strongly recommend my Front Lever Course, which contains my 10 years of coaching experience 😉

⠀
I've studied the biomechanics of one arm handstand and tested hundreds of preparational exercises with my students. Today I'll share with you my top 3 exercises for this element 🔥
⠀
1️⃣ ELEVATED PIKE STAND WEIGHT SHIFTS
⠀
Take an elevated pike stand position. Transfer your body weight to one arm leaning to the side and pushing your shoulder up as much as possible. Raise your free hand and touch the shoulder. Return to the initial position and repeat on the other side. Keep your back straight and your core tensed throughout the exercise.
⠀
💪 MUSCLES
Front deltoids
Middle deltoids
Trapezius
⠀
This exercise will teach you to transfer weight to one arm and push the shoulder off the floor.
⠀
2️⃣ BACK-TO-WALL ONE ARM HANDSTAND
⠀
In this exercise, you get exactly the amount of pressure on your shoulder needed in a freestanding one arm handstand!
⠀
Your body shouldn’t twist and the shoulder shouldn’t get over shrugged. Touch the wall with your feet only.
⠀
💪 MUSCLES
Front deltoids
Middle deltoids
Trapezius
Core
⠀
DON’T USE THIS EXERCISE AS ATTEMPTS TO ONE ARM HANDSTAND!
⠀
3️⃣ ONE ARM PIKE PUSH-UPS
⠀
Spread your legs. Keep your back straight and the core tensed.
Don't twist your body throughout the exercise.
⠀
In the initial position, push your shoulder off the floor to engage trapezius muscles.
⠀
💪 MUSCLES
Middle deltoids
Trapezius
⠀
The final phase of the exercise is kinda the movement that occurs when transferring from handstand to one arm handstand.
⠀
These exercises are aimed at strength. BUT strength is just one of the aspects needed for one arm handstand.
⠀

Hey, calisthenics community! Artem is here 👋
⠀
Only a few know that the lower back arching comes from the shoulder angle. When in handstand you have an angle in shoulders then your body automatically wants to compensate via throwing your legs over your head in order to catch balance. If you fix the shoulder angle, then the lower back arching will go away!
⠀
Run these simple tests to figure out your weak spots:
⠀
TEST 1️⃣
1. Stand sideways in front of a mirror.
2. Tighten your abs and twist your pelvis forward.
3. Bring your shoulders back and straighten your back.
4. Lift your hands up and pull them back over your head as far as possible.
⠀
If you get a straight body line from the hands to the heels, then your muscles are flexible enough and the problem lies in a lack of STRENGTH.
⠀
If you feel you can lift your hands that far but they just don't go there like hitting an invisible wall, then your problem is a lack of FLEXIBILITY.
⠀
TEST 2️⃣
1. Get into a pike stand position.
2. Completely relax your shoulders and drop in them forward
3. From this position try to move back to compensate the shoulder angle
4. Now try to push off the floor with your shoulders and fix the shoulders' angle
⠀
If you feel as you drop forward in the shoulders and can't push off the floor then your problem is STRENGTH.
⠀
👌 FIX FLEXIBILITY
Add a bit of shoulder stretching exercises before practising handstand and a lot of after each training session!
⠀
💪 FIX STRENGTH
Do more strengthening exercises for handstand that involves deltoids (shoulder muscles) and trapezius but keep an eye on the flexibility level as you become less flexible as your muscles get stronger. Add a couple of stretching exercises.
⠀

Hi, calisthenics community! Artem is here 👋
⠀
Lately, I've been asked a lot of "how to start learning front lever". Today I will clear this topic for you 😉
⠀
=========
⠀
First, let's figure out, which muscles work in the front lever. To do this, let's divide the approach to performing front lever into 2 parts:
⠀
1️⃣ Horizontal position of the body
⠀
In order to keep your body horizontal, the following muscles are involved in the work:
⠀
🔹 Lats
🔹 Trapezius
🔹 Posterior deltoid
🔹 Teres major and minor
⠀
Altogether, you need all the muscles of the upper back.
⠀
2️⃣ Straight front lever line
⠀
All core muscles work to keep your body straight:
⠀
🔹 Abdominals
🔹 Oblique muscles
🔹 Serratus
🔹 Gluteal muscles
🔹 Lower back muscles
⠀
=========
⠀
Your first step towards front lever is training those muscles.
⠀
Thus, most of the exercises in the program should be aimed at the back and core muscles, but don't forget about other muscles in order to develop comprehensively!
⠀
Minimal requirements for front lever:
⠀
✊ Pull-ups — 15+ reps
👊 Dips —  20+ reps
🖐 Push-ups — 30+ reps
⠀
If you still don't hit those numbers, don't worry. In my Basic Course, you'll find all the exercises and training programs needed to improve your basics. There's also a whole chapter devoted to preparing yourself for the front lever 😉
⠀
=========
⠀
After reaching these numbers, you are ready to move on to the next step — preparational exercises. Not only will they help you to strengthen the needed muscles, but also to learn how to properly engage them in the work to perform the front lever.
⠀
Do preparational exercises 2-3 times a week. The main load will be taken by back and core muscles, so do basics for the rest of the muscle groups once a week.
